we have the image and also the text just below.

00:03:37.235 --> 00:03:40.220
As you may expect to place this above the image,

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:42.320
this is going to take some CSS work.

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:45.320
So just placing this below the image is fine for now.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:50.275
But what we're first going to focus on is switching between our college image.

00:03:50.275 --> 00:03:55.730
We're going to download the college-small on a mobile device or a small screen.

00:03:55.730 --> 00:03:58.355
Then, once we reach a certain size,

00:03:58.355 --> 00:04:01.085
we're going to switch to the college.jpeg,

00:04:01.085 --> 00:04:02.905
which is a larger version.

00:04:02.905 --> 00:04:09.740
If we click on this, we can see the college-small is 1280 pixels wide,

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:12.380
whereas the college.jpeg is larger,

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:16.480
and it has the width 1920 pixels.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:20.405
Why would we want to include two separate images?

00:04:20.405 --> 00:04:23.950
Well, the reason for this is because of the download time,

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:26.360
and also the image quality.

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:31.890
If you think about having a mobile device on visiting this project on a small screen,

00:04:31.890 --> 00:04:34.930
if we have a slower mobile network connection,

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:37.940
we don't want to be downloading the large image.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:42.155
It would instead be a lot faster to download this smaller version.

00:04:42.155 --> 00:04:45.275
From the other side, if we are using a large monitor,

00:04:45.275 --> 00:04:48.320
if we were only to include a small image like this,

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.570
and then stretches to be a larger size,

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:53.200
it would lose a lot of quality.

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:57.320
To deal with this, we are going to make use of a HTML element called picture.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:00.875
This is going to allow us to provide multiple image sources,

00:05:00.875 --> 00:05:04.325
and then the browser can decide which one is the most appropriate.

00:05:04.325 --> 00:05:09.250
Well, to do this, we're going to include the picture elements.

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:13.840
We first include the picture elements as a wrapper,

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:16.370
we still need to include the image source,

00:05:16.370 --> 00:05:18.380
and then just above this,

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:21.490
we're going to use the HTML source element.

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:25.415
The source element doesn't include a opening and closing tag.

00:05:25.415 --> 00:05:28.160
Instead, we pass in some attributes.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:31.955
The first one is going to be a media query.

00:05:31.955 --> 00:05:35.270
A media query is also something which we're going to use inside of

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:40.115
our CSS to apply different styles to different screen sizes.

00:05:40.115 --> 00:05:42.335
But when used with the source,

00:05:42.335 --> 00:05:44.585
this is going to allow us to provide

00:05:44.585 --> 00:05:48.950
different size images for different media types or devices.

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:52.445
One of the most common use cases for a media query

00:05:52.445 --> 00:05:56.525
is to switch the content at a certain screen width.

00:05:56.525 --> 00:05:59.375
If we pass inside of the brackets,

00:05:59.375 --> 00:06:06.090
a minimum screen width of 1100 pixels.

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:11.785
This particular section will only apply when the browser is over 1100 pixels wide.

00:06:11.785 --> 00:06:14.150
Then once it is over the size,

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:16.850
we can then use the source set attribute,

00:06:16.850 --> 00:06:20.820
it provides this file path to our large image.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:25.340
There's lots of different media conditions which we can add.

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:27.605
We can include the maximum width.

00:06:27.605 --> 00:06:31.975
We can check for the device orientation to see if it's landscape or portrait.

00:06:31.975 --> 00:06:34.445
We can check the pixel ratio of a monitor,

00:06:34.445 --> 00:06:36.790
and lots of other different things.

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:42.710
This is going to apply our larger image if the browser's width is over 1100 pixels.

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:45.455
But if the browser width is below this size,

00:06:45.455 --> 00:06:49.595
it's going to fall back to this image element just here,

00:06:49.595 --> 00:06:51.845
which includes the small version.

00:06:51.845 --> 00:06:56.180
If we wanted to, we could insert as many source elements as we wanted to.

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:58.895
We could set up different media conditions,

00:06:58.895 --> 00:07:01.870
and also point these to different images too.

00:07:01.870 --> 00:07:05.415
Over this, our two image sizes are fine.

00:07:05.415 --> 00:07:09.755
Just as a side note, we always need to include this image element.

00:07:09.755 --> 00:07:12.260
This is because this is ultimately

00:07:12.260 --> 00:07:15.905
the element which is always going to be rendered inside the browser.

00:07:15.905 --> 00:07:19.190
All we're doing is switching around the different image sources.

00:07:19.190 --> 00:07:22.060
Make sure this is always included.

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:24.980
The way we can test this out, if we say this,

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:29.765
is to refresh the browser and open up the developer tools with right-click,

00:07:29.765 --> 00:07:35.880
and inspect, and into the Network tab.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:39.320
What we need to first do here is to shrink the browser down to

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:44.995
a small screen size which is below 1100 pixels, then refresh.

00:07:44.995 --> 00:07:49.040
From here, we have the small version of our image downloaded,

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:52.355
and this is 361 kilobytes.

